---
import Newspaper from "@/layouts/Newspaper.astro";
---

<Newspaper title="About — Lighthouse" section="ABOUT" pageHeading="What is Lighthouse?">
  <article class="max-w-column mx-auto font-serif text-[1.05rem] leading-[1.65]">
    <p>
      <strong>Lighthouse is a knowledge base for AI agents.</strong> Public
      reference material — IETF RFCs, OWASP cheat sheets, NIST SP-800,
      framework documentation, recognised practitioner writing — is
      crawled, chunked, embedded, summarised, and indexed in a
      Postgres + pgvector store. An MCP endpoint exposes a single
      <code>search</code> tool that any MCP-capable agent can wire up.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-display text-2xl mt-8 mb-2">Why a newspaper layout?</h3>
    <p>
      Agents are the primary consumer, but humans need a way to see
      what's in the corpus, what's freshly ingested, and what's
      missing. The broadsheet layout treats each chunk as a dispatch,
      sections as the corpus's roles, and the masthead as the daily
      snapshot. It's a UI for content auditing as much as discovery.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-display text-2xl mt-8 mb-2">How does retrieval work?</h3>
    <p>
      Each chunk has three text fields beyond the body: a Qwen-7B
      one-sentence summary, 3–5 topic tags, and 6–12 search-relevant
      keywords (synonyms and alternative phrasings). Search runs
      BM25 over a weighted tsvector (summary &amp; keywords A,
      tags B, content C), and cosine similarity over the chunk
      embedding. A reciprocal-rank-fusion merge passes the top
      candidates through a gpt-4o-mini reranker that scores each
      against the query directly.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-display text-2xl mt-8 mb-2">How does it differ from Context7?</h3>
    <p>
      Context7 ships a wide library-doc snapshot (hundreds of
      framework docs, thousands of snippets each). Lighthouse is
      narrower at Tier 1 — the most-used frameworks per role — and
      adds three layers Context7 doesn't index: canonical standards
      (RFCs, OWASP, NIST), practitioner literature (Fowler, Schneier,
      Cagan, Brendan Gregg), and post-cutoff streams (RSS feeds,
      release notes). Where the two overlap on library docs, our
      bet is depth via summarisation; where they don't overlap,
      we're the only place.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-display text-2xl mt-8 mb-2">Built in the open</h3>
    <p>
      The code lives at
      <a href="https://github.com/ElMundiUA/lighthouse">github.com/ElMundiUA/lighthouse</a>
      under Apache 2.0. The corpus is private (we pay for ingest);
      the retrieval engine is open. Run your own copy if you want
      a self-hosted reference for your team.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-display text-2xl mt-8 mb-2">Subscribing</h3>
    <p>
      Anonymous access has a small daily query budget. Registered
      readers get more. A paid tier (Pro) lifts the cap and adds
      access to <code>fetch_source</code> for the full article body.
      See <a href="/pricing">subscribe</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</Newspaper>
